__caption\">Jeremy Corbyn and Owen Smith. Corbyn remains the favourite to win the leadership election.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Danny Lawson/PA</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<h2>What has the court of appeal ruled?</h2> <p>The <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/labour\">Labour party</a>’s rules give its governing national executive committee the power to set the criteria for members to be eligible to vote in its <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/labourleadership\">leadership contest</a>. The NEC had previously ruled that those who had joined the party since 12 January would not be eligible to vote in the upcoming election.</p> <p>This decision was then struck down by the high court on <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/08/labour-must-allow-all-members-leadership-vote-court-rules\">8 August</a> following a crowdfunded challenge by five of the affected new members. On Friday the court of appeal found in favour of the NEC’s original decision, to the ire of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign which said this had potentially disenfranchised thousands of members.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/12/labour-party-appeal-leadership-election-decision-nec-corbyn-owen-smith\">Labour NEC wins voting appeal: our writers’ verdict | Polly Toynbee and David Wearing</a> </p> </aside>  <h2>How many people are affected by the ruling?</h2> <p>Some of the 130,000 new members who joined less than six months ago will not be able to vote in the forthcoming poll between Corbyn and Owen Smith for the Labour leadership.</p> <h2>So who can actually vote?</h2> <p>Three groups can vote: Labour members who joined before 12 January, members of affiliated unions, and registered supporters who took advantage of a window offered by the NEC from 18-20 July when recent members and non-members could pay £25 to become “registered supporters”.</p> <h2>Why was the six-month freeze implemented by the NEC?</h2> <p>In part, to reduce the administrative burden of verifying thousands of new members. However, Labour party’s general secretary, Iain McNicol, also made it clear in evidence that there have been concerns about a subversion of the voting process, with members joining with the sole purpose of voting in the election rather than participating in the party more widely.</p> <h2>Will the court of appeal’s ruling be challenged?</h2> <p>The appeal judges refused the five Labour members who originally challenged the NEC leave to appeal to the supreme court and ordered them to pay costs. However, the five members’ lawyers can still ask the supreme court justices directly to consider their case. David Goldstone QC, who had represented the five, indicated in court that steps had already been taken which could lead to a hearing next Tuesday.</p> <h2>What does the verdict mean in monetary terms?</h2> <p>Potentially a very large bill for the five new members who brought the case. They must pay £30,000 towards the NEC’s costs, which are £60,000 in total, within 28 days. The party itself also avoids a bill for refunding all of the excluded new members who had also later paid the £25. This had been estimated to be in the region of £1.25m.</p> <h2>How likely is the ruling to impact on the final result of the leadership contest?</h2> <p>Supporters of both Corbyn and Smith believe that the majority of the 130,000 who joined in the weeks running up to the beginning of the challenge against Corbyn have done so to back the current leader. While bookmakers have cut Smith’s odds in the wake of the latest ruling, Corbyn remains the favourite to win, thanks in part to the many members who originally joined to vote for him in <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/12/jeremy-corbyn-wins-labour-party-leadership-election\">last year’s leadership contest</a>.</p> <h2>What do the polls close and when will the result be known?</h2> <p>The closing date is noon on 21 September. The result will be announced at the Labour party conference on 24 September.</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"6","wordcount":"555","creationDate":"2016-08-12T16:01:08Z","firstPublicationDate":"2016-08-12T18:07:07Z","internalComposerCode":"57adf2c4e4b007f802bad701","internalOctopusCode":"11807095","internalPageCode":"2650881","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2016-08-12T22:05:01Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2016-08-13T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4qt8y","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/e39ed1438befd51e20b12afd207271dbc66a06ba/0_581_3512_2107/500.jpg","legallySensitive":"false","lang":"en","internalRevision":"357","internalShortId":"/p/4qt8y"},"apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2016/aug/12/labour-leadership-court-of-appeal-ruling-nec-membership","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/12/labour-leadership-court-of-appeal-ruling-nec-membership","webTitle":"Labour leadership court of appeal ruling: all you need to know","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-12T18:07:07Z","sectionName":"Politics","sectionId":"politics","type":"article","id":"politics/2016/aug/12/labour-leadership-court-of-appeal-ruling-nec-membership","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"section":{"id":"politics","webTitle":"Politics","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/politics","editions":[{"id":"politics","webTitle":"Politics","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/politics","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false}},{"metadata":{"id":"internal-code/page/2647031","articleType":"article","group":"included"},"content":{"references":[{"id":"rich-link/https://www.theguardian.com